The largest possible value of $|x|+|y|$ occurs when $(x,y)$ lies on one of the coordinate axes.  Without loss of generality, assume $x \ge 0.$  Then $y^2 = 1 - x^2,$ so
\[|x| + |y| = x + \sqrt{1 - x^2}.\]Let $f(x) = x + \sqrt{1 - x^2}.$  Then $f'(x) = 1 - \frac{x}{\sqrt{1 - x^2}},$ which is 0 when $x = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}.$  Furthermore, $f''(x) = -\frac{1}{(1 - x^2)^{3/2}},$ so $f''(x) < 0$ when $0 < x < \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}},$ which means $f(x)$ is concave down on $[0,\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}].$

Therefore, the maximum occurs at $x = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}},$ and the maximum value is
\[\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} + \sqrt{1 - \frac{1}{2}} = \boxed{\sqrt{2}}.\]
